  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Nutrition Response in Six Woredas of Erer and Nogob Zones, Somali Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Save the Children proposes provision of lifesaving, emergency nutrition services for 25,334 beneficiaries (--girls, ---boys, ---women, ----men) to reduce morbidity and mortality of infants, young children and pregnant and lactating women (PLW) in drought affected communities of Somali Region, Ethiopia. Target locations include the following priority 1 hotspot woredas: Fik, Hamaro, Yohob, Wangey (Erer) and Ayun, Sagag (Nogob). The proposed project will prevent, detect and treat acute malnutrition through integrated Management of Acute Malnutrition (IMAM) including Therapeutic Feeding (TF) for severely acutely (SAM) malnourished children and Targeted Supplementary Feeding (TSF) for moderately malnourished (MAM) children 6 to 59 months old and malnourished PLW. The project will support prevention of acute malnutrition through improvement of optimal Infant and Young Child Feeding in Emergency (IYCF-E) practices for infants and young children under 24 months and support the nutritional needs of pregnant and lactating women (PLW). Project targets are as follows: 1,182 cases of SAM and 9,852 cases of MAM. 80% of MAM cases and PLW will receive TSFP services. Save the Children will ensure continuum of care by linking OTP discharged children with TSFP in all areas.

In line with the Midyear 2018 Ethiopian Humanitarian and Disaster Resilience Plan (HDRP), the proposed project will deliver a full-spectrum emergency nutrition intervention including prevention, treatment, management, community mobilization and case identification, and key capacity building for Regional health bureaus and health workers to achieve and sustain impact. Exceptionally vulnerable women and children in drought-affected and conflict induced communities will be prioritized for services</narrative>
  </description>
